07154nam a22018135i 9780691229867DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912298677 a10.1515/97806912298672doi  a(DE-B1597)627740  a(OCoLC)1336990500  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0020002bisacsh1 aDiogenes, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow to Say No :bAn Ancient Guide to the Art of Cynicism /cDiogenes. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAncient Wisdom for Modern Readers00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tDedicatory Poem -- tIntroduction -- t1. Life Is a Dog -- t2. How Not to Say No -- t3. Cynic in Swaddling Clothes -- t4. My Friend Demetrius -- t5. Student Tribute -- t6. A Passage to India -- t7. Best in Show -- t8. Interview with a Cynic -- t9. Know Thyself! -- t10. The Columnist -- tNotes -- tPassages Translated -- tSuggestions for Further Reading0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn entertaining and enlightening collection of ancient writings about the philosophers who advocated simple living and rejected unthinking conformityThe Cynics were ancient Greek philosophers who stood athwart the flood of society’s material excess, unexamined conventions, and even norms of politeness and thundered “No!” Diogenes, the most famous Cynic, wasn’t shy about literally extending his middle finger to the world, expressing mock surprise that “most people go crazy over a finger.” When asked why he was called Diogenes the Dog, he replied “because I fawn on those who give, I bark at those who don’t, and I bite scoundrels.” How to Say No is a delightful collection of brief ancient writings about Cynicism that captures all the outrageousness, wit, and wisdom of its remarkable cast of characters—from Diogenes in the fourth century BCE to the column-stander Symeon Stylites in late antiquity.With their “less is more” approach to life, the Cynics speak urgently to our world of climate change, economic uncertainty, and psychic malaise. Although the Cynics weren’t writers, their memorable utterances and behavior were recorded by their admirers and detractors, and M. D. Usher offers fresh new translations of appealing selections from this body of writing—ranging from street sermons and repartee to biography and snapshots of Cynics in action.Complete with introductions to the volume and each selection as well as the original Greek and Latin on facing pages, this lively book demonstrates why the Cynics still retain their power to surprise us and make us laugh—and to make us think and question how we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAnecdote.  aAwareness.  aAxis powers.  aBeech.  aBehavior.  aBorysthenes.  aCatamite.  aChicory.  aClothing.  aCornelius Nepos.  aCowardice.  aCrates of Thebes.  aCriticism.  aCritique.  aCuisine.  aCynic epistles.  aCynicism (contemporary).  aCynicism (philosophy).  aDe Beneficiis.  aDecision-making.  aDegrowth.  aDemagogue.  aDemetrius the Cynic.  aDemonax.  aDiogenes of Sinope.  aDisgust.  aDoctrine.  aDrought.  aEarthenware.  aEclecticism.  aEpicurus.  aEpistle.  aEssay.  aExplanation.  aExternality.  aForehead.  aFrugality.  aGauls.  aGood and evil.  aGreek Philosophy.  aGreek War of Independence.  aHairstyle.  aHassle.  aHinge.  aHousehold.  aHusk.  aIamblichus.  aIoannis Metaxas.  aKnow thyself.  aLaziness.  aLentil.  aLettuce.  aMalaise.  aMartyr.  aMeletus.  aMiscellany.  aModern 